Producers of the long-running Chicago Public Radio program  announced Monday that they have completed their comprehensive 12-year survey of life as a modern upper-middle-class American.In what cultural anthropologists are calling a "colossal achievement" in the study of white-collar professionals, the popular radio show has successfully isolated all 7,442 known characteristics of college graduates who earn between $62,500 and $125,000 per year and feel strongly that something should be done about global warming.